1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,387
Imagine you are studying English. Perhaps you are learning new words or expressions.

2
00:00:07,387 --> 00:00:14,507
But then you feel the need to check your phone. Perhaps you look on social media.

3
00:00:14,507 --> 00:00:21,392
You return to your studies, only to look again at your phone a short time later.

4
00:00:21,392 --> 00:00:29,611
This process, when repeated many times, could reduce your ability to learn new material.

5
00:00:29,611 --> 00:00:40,808
It is what you might call a bad habit – a custom or repeated action that has a negative effect on you or your goals.

6
00:00:40,808 --> 00:00:50,379
Today, on Education Tips, we will explore how you can break bad habits, such as repeatedly checking your phone.

7
00:00:50,379 --> 00:00:55,845
In an earlier Education Tips story, we explored habits.

8
00:00:55,845 --> 00:01:00,904
Habits are ways of dealing with issues in your environment.

9
00:01:00,904 --> 00:01:03,448
You often do not think about them.

10
00:01:03,448 --> 00:01:08,632
In the earlier report, we discussed how habits are made.

11
00:01:08,632 --> 00:01:11,637
Now, a quick reminder for you.

12
00:01:11,637 --> 00:01:20,989
James Clear, in his book Atomic Habits, describes a four-step process by which habits are made.

13
00:01:20,989 --> 00:01:27,040
These steps are cue, craving, response, and reward.

14
00:01:27,040 --> 00:01:34,360
A cue is a signal. It tells your brain to do something: to begin a behavior.

15
00:01:34,360 --> 00:01:38,125
A craving is a desire for something.

16
00:01:38,125 --> 00:01:43,619
The response, or reaction, is the habit that you perform.

17
00:01:43,619 --> 00:01:46,741
The response gives you a reward.

18
00:01:46,741 --> 00:01:51,829
“Rewards are the end goal of every habit,” Clear writes.

19
00:01:51,829 --> 00:01:57,805
In our cell phone example, the cue is seeing the cell phone.

20
00:01:57,805 --> 00:02:02,557
The craving is the desire or urge to check your phone.

21
00:02:02,557 --> 00:02:05,739
The response is checking your phone.

22
00:02:05,739 --> 00:02:12,184
The reward might be seeing something interesting on social media, for example.

23
00:02:12,184 --> 00:02:21,624
James Clear notes that to break bad habits, you need to think about each step in the habit-making process.

24
00:02:21,624 --> 00:02:32,909
To break a habit, he writes, you should think about making the bad habit invisible, unattractive, difficult and unsatisfying.

25
00:02:32,909 --> 00:02:37,192
To make your phone invisible, you could hide it away.

26
00:02:37,192 --> 00:02:44,512
To make it unattractive, you could think about why it is a good idea to stop checking the phone.

27
00:02:44,512 --> 00:02:51,035
To make phone use difficult, you can increase the space between you and your phone.

28
00:02:51,035 --> 00:02:56,832
To make your phone unsatisfying, you could make a habit contract.

29
00:02:56,832 --> 00:03:05,325
For example, you could ask a family member to watch your behavior and point out when you check your phone.

30
00:03:05,325 --> 00:03:12,939
You could promise to pay that person every time you look at the device while you are studying.

31
00:03:12,939 --> 00:03:18,211
Wendy Wood is a psychologist and an expert on habits.

32
00:03:18,211 --> 00:03:28,208
In the book Good Habits, Bad Habits, she offers some ideas on how people can cut back on their cell phone use.

33
00:03:28,208 --> 00:03:32,240
One suggestion is to wear a wristwatch.

34
00:03:32,240 --> 00:03:38,477
This will limit at least one reason for looking at the phone – checking the time.

35
00:03:38,477 --> 00:03:47,163
Wood notes the importance of increasing the number of steps you need to take in order to use your cell phone.

36
00:03:47,163 --> 00:03:55,149
“Silence it. Turn it off. Switch on your phone’s Do Not Disturb mode,” she writes.

37
00:03:55,149 --> 00:04:01,885
She adds that you can move your phone to a place that is more difficult to reach.

38
00:04:01,885 --> 00:04:06,520
For example, you can put your phone inside a backpack.

39
00:04:06,520 --> 00:04:11,653
Wood also suggests another way to think about cell phone use.

40
00:04:11,653 --> 00:04:17,573
She says you can add a new, healthy habit onto your cell phone habit.

41
00:04:17,573 --> 00:04:28,360
“What about if every time you check your phone, you call one member of your family just to say hello and have a quick … chat?” she asks.

42
00:04:28,360 --> 00:04:38,877
Finally, Wood suggests one kind of reward you could give yourself for not looking at your phone: reading a good book.

43
00:04:38,877 --> 00:04:44,029
Today, we discussed ideas for reducing your cell phone use.

44
00:04:44,029 --> 00:04:48,323
But you can use these ideas to break other behaviors.

45
00:04:48,323 --> 00:04:54,115
The important thing to remember is that people can change their habits.

46
00:04:54,115 --> 00:05:00,317
But they must think carefully about their surroundings or environment.

47
00:05:00,317 --> 00:05:10,904
You might decide to stop doing an action, but if such an action is very easy for you to do, you will probably continue doing it.

48
00:05:10,904 --> 00:05:18,821
Habit changes take time. But with patience, planning, and repetition, you can do it.

49
00:05:18,821 --> 00:05:21,280
I’m John Russell.